ocation =Gulf Breeze, FL |publisher=Academic International Press |url=http://www.ai-press.com/NET.html |isbn=978-0-87569-205-0 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://nationalityinworldhistory.net/index.html |title=Nationality: The History of a Social Phenomenon |last1= White |first1= Philip L. |authorlink1=Philip L. White|last2= White |first2= Michael Lee |year=2008 |work=Nationality in World History}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links|voy=no}}\n* [https://www.britannica.com/topic/nationalism Nationalism] \u2014 entry at ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]''    \n* {{cite web |url=http://www.fordham.edu/Halsall/mod/modsbook17.asp |title=Nationalism |work=Internet Modern History Sourcebook |publisher=[[Fordham University]]}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.nationalismproject.org/ |title=The Nationalism Project |date= |work=Association for Research on Ethnicity and Nationalism in the Americas |publisher=[[University of South Carolina]]}}\n* [http://polyarchy.org/references/nationalism.html Nationalism : selected references]\n\n{{Nationalism}}\n{{Political ideologies}}\n{{Conformity}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Nationalism| ]]\n[[Category:Political theories]]\n", "name_user": "218.186.154.64", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nationalism"}
{"title_page": "George Clooney", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{short description|American actor, filmmaker, and activist}}\n{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = George Clooney\n| image              = George Clooney 2016.jpg\n| alt                = Upper body photo, he is wearing white clothes\n| caption            = Clooney in September 2016\n| birth_name         = George Timothy Clooney\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1961|5|6}}\n| birth_place        = [[Lexington, Kentucky]], U.S.\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| residence          = [[Sonning Eye]], [[Oxfordshire]], England<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hellomagazine.com/celebrities/2015052025353/george-clooney-amal-clooney-move-to-england-summer/ |title=George Clooney confirms he and Amal are moving to England |publisher=hellomagazine |accessdate=May 20, 2015 |date=May 20, 2015}}</ref>\n| occupation         = [[Actor]], [[Film director|director]], [[Film producer|producer]], [[Filmmaking|filmmaker]]\n| education          = [[Northern Kentucky University]]\n| years_active       = 1978\u2013present\n| net_worth          = $ 500 million (2020)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/photos/entertainment/meet-the-worlds-richest-movie-star-an-indian-shah-rukh-khan-1.1578313981556?slide=13|first=Shreya|last=Bhatia|title=Meet the world's richest movie star, an Indian: Shah Rukh Khan|date=January 6, 2020|website=[[Gulf News]]}}</ref>\n\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Talia Balsam]]|1989|1993|end=divorced}}<br>{{Marriage|[[Amal Clooney|Amal Alamuddin]]|September 27, 2014}}\n| children           = 2\n| father             = [[Nick Clooney]]\n| relatives          = {{Plain list|\n* [[Rosemary Clooney]] (aunt)\n* [[Miguel Ferrer]] (cousin)\n* [[Rafael Ferrer (actor)|Rafael Ferrer]] (cousin)\n* [[Betty Clooney]] (aunt)\n}}\n}}\n\n'''George Timothy Clooney''' (born May 6, 1961) is an American actor, director, producer and filmmaker. He is the recipient of three [[Golden Globes|Golden Globe Awards]] and two [[Academy Awards]], one for acting in ''[[Syriana]]'' (2006) and the other for co-producing ''[[Argo (2012 film)|Argo]]'' (2012). In 2018, he was the recipient of the [[American Film Institute|AFI]] Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.afi.com/laa/laa18.aspx |title=American Film Institute - 2018 George Clooney Tribute |website=www.afi.com|access-date=October 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nClooney made his acting debut on television in 1978, and later gained wide recognition in his role as Dr. [[Doug Ross]] on the medical drama ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'' from 1994 to 1999, for which he received two [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations. While working on ''ER'', he began attracting a variety of leading roles in films, with his breakthrough role in ''[[From Dusk till Dawn]]'' (1996),<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://variety.com/1996/film/reviews/from-dusk-till-dawn-1200444406/ |title=From Dusk Till Dawn |last=McCarthy |first=Todd |date=January 22, 1996 |work=Variety|access-date=September 12, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.amiannoying.com/(S(h1nq2y424dtgh2xkboty2hue))/collection.aspx?collection=1301 |title=AmIAnnoying.com - MTV Movie Awards: Breakthrough Performance |website=www.amiannoying.com|access-date=September 12, 2018}}</ref> and the crime comedy ''[[Out of Sight (1998 film)|Out of Sight]]'' (1998), in which he first worked with director [[Steven Soderbergh]], who would become a long-time collaborator. In 1999, he took the lead role in ''[[Three Kings (1999 film)|Three Kings]]'', a well-received war satire set during the [[Gulf War]].\n\nIn 2001, Clooney's fame widened with the release of his biggest commercial success, the heist comedy remake ''[[Ocean's Eleven]]'', the first of what became [[Ocean's (film series)|a trilogy]], starring Clooney. He made his directorial debut a year later with the biographical spy comedy ''[[Confessions of a Dangerous Mind (film)|Confessions of a Dangerous Mind]]'', and has since directed the historical drama ''[[Good Night, and Good Luck]]'' (2005), the sports comedy ''[[Leatherheads]]'' (2008), the political drama ''[[The Ides of March (2011 film)|The Ides of March]]'' (2011), and the war film ''[[The Monuments Men]]'' (2014). Clooney won an Academy Award for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for the Middle East thriller ''[[Syriana]]'' (2005), and subsequently earned [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] nominations for the legal thriller ''[[Michael Clayton (film)|Michael Clayton]]'' (2007) and the comedy-dramas ''[[Up in the Air (2009 film)|Up in the Air]]'' (2009) and ''[[The Descendants]]'' (2011). In 2013, he received the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]] for producing the political thriller ''[[Argo (2012 film)|Argo]]''. He has been nominated for Oscars in six different categories, a record he shares with [[Walt Disney]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://uproxx.com/hitfix/ |title=HitFix |publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://deadline.com/2013/02/oscars-george-clooney-king-academy-awards-436446/ |title=OSCARS: Is George Clooney Now King Of The Academy Awards? |last=Hammond |first=Pete |date=February 21, 2013 |work=Deadline|access-date=September 6, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Clooney was included in ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'s}} annual [[Time 100]] as one of the \"Most Influential People in the World\".<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Bono |title=George Clooney \u2013 The 2009 TIME 100 |url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1894410_1894289_1894280,00.html |journal=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |accessdate=June 10, 2014 |date=April 30, 2009|author1-link=Bono}}</ref> He is also noted for his political and economic activism, and has served as one of the [[United Nations Messengers of Peace]] since January 31, 2008.<ref name=\"peace\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idUSN1833517620080118?feedType=RSS&feedName=domesticNews&rpc=22&sp=true |title=George Clooney named UN messenger of peace |agency=Reuters |date=January 18, 2008 |first=Patrick |last=Worsnip}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc1\">{{cite news |title=UN gives actor Clooney peace role |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7220701.stm |work=BBC News |date=February 1, 2008 |accessdate=July 5, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.betterworldcampaign.org/peace |title=Clooney PSA Announcement |publisher=Better World Campaign |accessdate=September 19, 2009}}</ref> Clooney is also a member of the [[Council on Foreign Relations]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cfr.org/about/membership/roster.html?letter=C |title=Membership Roster |publisher=Council on Foreign Relations |accessdate=January 31, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110803033745/http://www.cfr.org/about/membership/roster.html?letter=C |archive-date=August 3, 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref> He is married to human rights lawyer [[Amal Clooney]].\n\n==Early life==\nClooney was born on May 6, 1961 in [[Lexington, Kentucky]].<ref name=\"Esquire\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/US/01/18/mip.monday/ |publisher=CNN |title=Intriguing people for January 18, 2010 |date=January 18, 2010}}</ref> His mother, Nina Bruce (n\u00e9e Warren),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.genealogy.com/famousfolks/george-clooney/d0/i0000005.htm#s2 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020805101303/http://www5.genealogy.com/famousfolks/george-clooney/d0/i0000005.htm |publisher=Genealogy.com |archivedate=August 5, 2002 |title=Second Generation}}</ref> was a [[beauty pageant|beauty queen]] and [[city councilwoman]]. His father, [[Nick Clooney]], is a former [[News presenter|anchorman]] and television host, including five years on the [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] network.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nick Joseph Clooney (D) |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/elections/2004/candidates/22111/ |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=June 10, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140906201250/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/elections/2004/candidates/22111/ |archive-date=September 6, 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Clooney is of [[Irish people|Irish]], [[Germanic peoples|German]], and [[English people|English]] ancestry.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Eig |first=Jonathan |title=The voice of experience Stormy life lends emotion to Clooney's singing |work=The Dallas Morning News |date=September 1, 1992 |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DM&p_theme=dm&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0ED3D262C9330137&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D |accessdate=December 4, 2011}}</ref> His maternal great-great-great-great-grandmother, Mary Ann Sparrow, was the half-sister of [[Nancy Lincoln]], mother of President [[Abraham Lincoln]].<ref>{{cite web |title=George Clooney is distantly related to Abraham Lincoln \u2013 Seven other celebs with famous ancestors |url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2012/11/02/george-clooney-abraham-lincoln/ |work=Entertainment Weekly |accessdate=April 28, 2014 |author=Tara Fowler |date=November 2, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=George Clooney and Abraham Lincoln are (distantly) related, ancestry website says |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/george-clooney-and-abraham-lincoln-are-distantly-related-ancestry-website-says/ |publisher=CBS News |accessdate=April 28, 2014 |author=Jessica Derschowitz |date=November 1, 2012}}</ref><ref>[http://people.com/celebrity/george-clooney-distantly-related-to-abraham-lincoln/ George Clooney Is (Distantly) Related to Abraham Lincoln] ''people.com'', November 1, 2012. Retrieved January 24, 2017.</ref> Clooney has an older sister named Adelia (known as Ada).<ref>{{cite web |author1=Sheila Marikar |title=Seven Things to Know About George Clooney's Sister |url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/entertainment/2012/11/seven-things-to-know-about-george-clooneys-sister/ |publisher=ABC News |accessdate=June 10, 2014 |date=November 9, 2012}}</ref> Cabaret singer and actress [[Rosemary Clooney]] was an aunt.<ref name=\"Esquire\"/> Through Rosemary, his cousins include actors [[Miguel Ferrer]], [[Rafael Ferrer (actor)|Rafael Ferrer]], and Gabriel Ferrer, who is married to singer [[Debby Boone]].<ref>{{cite web |author1=Nicki Gostin |title=Debby Boone talks living at Frank Sinatra's house, defends dad against critics |url=http://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/2013/07/08/debby-boone-talks-living-at-frank-sinatra-house-defends-dad-against-critics/ |publisher=Fox News Channel |accessdate=June 10, 2014 |date=July 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\nClooney was raised a strict [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.exacteditions.com/exact/browse/397/440/2440/3/16 |title=I used to go to confession every week |work=[[The Catholic Herald]] |date=December 22, 2006 |accessdate=May 6, 2010 |first=Gabrielle |last=Donnelly}}</ref> but said in 2006 that he did not know if he believed \"in Heaven, or even God.\"<ref name=\"Parade\">{{cite news |url=http://www.parade.com/articles/editions/1998/edition_06-07-1998/In_Step_With |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060322120931/http://www.parade.com/articles/editions/1998/edition_06-07-1998/In_Step_With |archivedate=March 22, 2006 |title='It's Finally About Friendship And Loyalty' |work=[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]] |accessdate=December 30, 2010 |first=Dotson |last=Rader}}</ref> He has said, \"Yes, we were Catholic, big-time, whole family, whole group.\"<ref name=CNN1>{{cite news |url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0602/16/lkl.01.html |title=CNN Larry King Live; Interview with George Clooney |publisher=CNN |date=February 16, 2006 |accessdate=May 6, 2010 |first=Larry |last=King}}</ref> He began his education at the Blessed Sacrament School in [[Fort Mitchell, Kentucky]]. He attended St. Michael's School in [[Worthington, Ohio]]; then Western Row Elementary School (a public school) in [[Mason, Ohio]], from 1968 to 1974; and St. Susanna School in Mason, where he served as an altar boy. The Clooneys moved back to Kentucky when George was midway through the seventh grade.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Rachel Richardson |title=George Clooney developed star power in Mason |url=http://www.cincinnati.com/story/news/local/mason/2014/06/04/george-clooney-developed-star-power-mason/9953593/ |newspaper=Cincinnati.com |accessdate=June 10, 2014 |date=June 4, 2014}}</ref> In middle school, Clooney developed [[Bell's palsy]], a medical condition that partially paralyzes the face. The malady went away within a year. In an interview with [[Larry King]], he stated that \"yes, it goes away. It takes about nine months to go away. It was the first year of high school, which was a bad time for having half your face paralyzed.\"<ref name=CNN1 /> He also described one positive outcome of the condition: \"It's probably a great thing that it happened to me because it forced me to engage in a series of making fun of myself. And I think that's an important part of being famous. The practical jokes have to be aimed at you.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=15033860 |title=George Clooney Returns as 'Michael Clayton' |publisher=}}</ref>\n\nAfter his parents moved to [[Augusta, Kentucky]], Clooney attended [[Augusta High School (Kentucky)|Augusta High School]]. He has stated that he earned all As and a B in school,<ref name=Esquire>{{cite magazine |first=A. J. |last=Jacobs |title=The 9:10 to Crazyland |url=http://www.esquire.com/features/george-clooney-0408 |magazine=Esquire |date=March 17, 2008 |accessdate=March 21, 2008}}</ref> and played baseball and basketball. He tried out to play professional baseball with the [[Cincinnati Reds]] in 1977, but he did not pass the first round of player cuts and was not offered a contract.<ref name=\"nina\">Clooney, Nina. [http://www.clooneystudio.com/biography.html George Clooney well-rooted in N. Ky. Clooney Studio. August 21, 2006.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070512232844/http://www.clooneystudio.com/biography.html |date=May 12, 2007 }}</ref> He attended [[Northern Kentucky University]] from 1979 to 1981, majoring in broadcast journalism, and very briefly attended the [[University of Cincinnati]], but did not graduate from either.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2waASQkzSJIC&pg=PA195 |title=George Clooney: the last great movie star |author=Kimberly Potts |accessdate=January 31, 2012 |isbn=9781557837219 |year=2007}}</ref> He earned money selling women's shoes, insurance door-to-door, stocking shelves, working in construction, and cutting tobacco.<ref name=\"Parade\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=George Clooney says acting is not hard |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/film-news/8937524/George-Clooney-says-acting-is-not-hard.html |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=April 28, 2014 |date=December 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early work, 1978\u20131993===\nClooney's first role was as an [[Extra (acting)|extra]] in the television mini-series ''[[Centennial (miniseries)|Centennial]]'' in 1978, which was based on the [[Centennial (novel)|novel of the same name]] by [[James A. Michener]] and was partly filmed in Clooney's hometown of Augusta, Kentucky.<ref>{{cite book |author1=Kimberly Potts |title=George Clooney : The Last Great Movie Star |date=2011 |publisher=Applause Theatre & Cinema Books |location=Montclair, NJ |isbn=978-1-55783-785-1 |page=217 |edition=Rev. and updated |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q6EHHXqbXpQC&pg=PA284&lpg=PA284#v=onepage&q=george%20clooney%2C%20Centennial |accessdate=June 17, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author1=Mark Browning |title=George Clooney : an actor looking for a role |date=2012 |publisher=Praeger |location=Santa Barbara, Calif. |isbn=978-0-313-39621-2 |page=1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BXaA1mCr93IC&pg=PA1&lpg=PA1#v=onepage&q=george%20clooney%2C%20Centennial |accessdate=June 17, 2014}}</ref> Clooney's first major role came in 1984 in the short-lived sitcom ''[[E/R]]'' (not to be confused with ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'', the better-known hospital drama, on which Clooney also co-starred a decade later). He played a handyman on the series ''[[The Facts of Life (TV series)|The Facts of Life]]'' and appeared as Bobby Hopkins, a detective, on an episode of ''[[The Golden Girls]]''. His first prominent role was a semi-regular supporting role in the sitcom ''[[Roseanne (TV series)|Roseanne]]'', playing [[Roseanne Barr]]'s supervisor Booker Brooks, followed by the role of a construction worker on ''[[Baby Talk (TV series)|Baby Talk]]'', a co-starring role on the CBS drama ''[[Bodies of Evidence (TV series)|Bodies of Evidence]]'' as Detective Ryan Walker, and then a year-long turn as Det. James Falconer on ''[[Sisters (U.S. TV series)|Sisters]]''. In 1988, Clooney played a small role in the comedy-horror film ''[[Return of the Killer Tomatoes]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=George Clooney; Wrong 'Tomatoes' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/07/09/movies/l-george-clooney-wrong-tomatoes-090387.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=July 28, 2014 |date=July 9, 2000}}</ref> In 1990, he starred in the short-lived [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] police drama ''[[Sunset Beat]]''.<ref>Terrace, Vincent. ''Encyclopedia of Television Shows, 1925 through 2007 (Jefferson, North Carolina: McFarland & Co., 2008), pp.1468-9.</ref> During this period, Clooney was a student at the [[Beverly Hills Playhouse]] acting school for five years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bhplayhouse.com/george-clooney |title=George Clooney on the Beverly Hills Playhouse Acting School |accessdate=July 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Breakthrough, 1994\u20131999===\n[[File:George Clooney 1995.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Clooney in 1995]]\nClooney rose to fame when he played Dr. [[Doug Ross]], alongside [[Anthony Edwards]], [[Julianna Margulies]], and [[Noah Wyle]], on the hit NBC medical drama ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'' from 1994 to 1999. After leaving the series in 1999, he made a [[cameo appearance]] in the 6th season and returned for a guest spot in the show's final season.<ref>{{cite web |title=ER Bringing Back Clooney with Margulies before Checking Out |url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/ER-Clooney-Margulies-1002020.aspx |work=TV Guide |year=2009 |accessdate=January 21, 2009}}</ref> For his work on the series, Clooney received two [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series]] in 1995 and 1996.<ref>{{cite web |title=Primetime Emmy nominations for 1995\u2013Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series |url=http://www.emmys.com/nominations/1995/Outstanding%20Lead%20Actor%20In%20A%20Drama%20Series |publisher=Emmys |accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Primetime Emmy nominations for 1996\u2013Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series |url=http://www.emmys.com/nominations/1996/OUTSTANDING%20LEAD%20ACTOR%20FOR%20A%20DRAMA%20SERIES |publisher=Emmys |accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref> He also earned three [[Golden Globe Award]] nominations for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Drama|Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Drama]] in 1995, 1996, and 1997 (losing to co-star [[Anthony Edwards]]).<ref>{{cite web |title=The 54th Annual Golden Globe Awards (1997) |url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/?param=/year/1996 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130521182756/http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/?param=%2Fyear%2F1996 |archivedate=May 21, 2013 |publisher=Hollywood Foreign Press Association |accessdate=January 24, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The 54th Annual Golden Globe Awards (1998) |url=http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/?param=/year/1997 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130521174533/http://www.goldenglobes.org/browse/?param=%2Fyear%2F1997 |archivedate=May 21, 2013 |publisher=Hollywood Foreign Press Association |accessdate=January 24, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref>\n\nClooney began appearing in films while working on ''ER''. His first major Hollywood role was in the horror comedy-crime thriller ''[[From Dusk till Dawn]]'', directed by [[Robert Rodriguez]] and co-starring [[Harvey Keitel]]. He followed its success with the romantic comedy ''[[One Fine Day (film)|One Fine Day]]'' with [[Michelle Pfeiffer]], and the action-thriller ''[[The Peacemaker (1997 film)|The Peacemaker]]'' with [[Nicole Kidman]]. Clooney was then cast as [[Batman]] in [[Joel Schumacher]]'s ''[[Batman & Robin (film)|Batman & Robin]]'', which was a modest box office performer, but a critical failure (with Clooney himself calling the film \"a waste of money\").<ref>{{cite web |first=Jack |last=Shepherd |title=George Clooney apologises for 'destroying' Batman & Robin 18 years later |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/george-clooney-apologises-for-destroying-batman--robin-18-years-later-10276879.html |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=May 26, 2015 |accessdate=September 19, 2015}}</ref> In 1998, he co-starred in the crime-comedy ''[[Out of Sight]]'' opposite [[Jennifer Lopez]], marking the first of his many collaborations with director [[Steven Soderbergh]].<ref>{{cite news |title=He's a Thief, She's a Marshal, They're an Item |url=https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9B05E5DB103AF935A15755C0A96E958260 |accessdate=September 19, 2015 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 26, 1998}}</ref> He also starred in ''[[Three Kings (1999 film)|Three Kings]]'' during the last weeks of his contract with ''ER''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Three Kings |url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/three-kings-1999 |publisher=rogerebert.com |accessdate=September 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===After ''ER'', 2000\u20132010===\n[[File:GeorgeClooneyGraumanHandFootprintsOct10.jpg|thumb|George Clooney cast his hands and shoes in the [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre]] in 2007.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6725463.stm |title=Clooney adds mark to Walk of Fame |date=June 6, 2007 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=September 13, 2009}}</ref>]]\n\nAfter leaving ''ER'', Clooney starred in the commercially successful films ''[[The Perfect Storm (film)|The Perfect Storm]]'' (2000), a disaster drama; and ''[[O Brother, Where Art Thou?]]'' (2000), a [[Coen brothers]] adventure comedy. In 2001, he teamed up with Soderbergh again for the heist comedy ''[[Ocean's Eleven (2001 film)|Ocean's Eleven]]'', a [[remake]] of the 1960s [[Rat Pack]] film [[Ocean's Eleven (1960 film)|of the same name]], with Clooney playing [[Danny Ocean (character)|Danny Ocean]], originally portrayed by [[Frank Sinatra]]. It is Clooney's most successful film with him in the lead role, earning $451&nbsp;million worldwide (he appeared, but did not star, in ''Gravity'', which has a $723 million worldwide box office).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=gravity.htm |title=Gravity (2013) - Box Office Mojo |website=www.boxofficemojo.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=oceanseleven.htm |title=Ocean's Eleven (2001) - Box Office Mojo |website=www.boxofficemojo.com}}</ref> The film inspired two sequels starring Clooney, ''[[Ocean's Twelve]]'' in 2004<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Lisa |last=Schwartzbaum |title=Ocean's Twelve |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2004/12/08/oceans-twelve |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=December 8, 2004 |accessdate=September 19, 2015}}</ref> and ''[[Ocean's Thirteen]]'' in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ocean's Thirteen GEORGE CLOONEY AND MATT DAMON INTERVIEW |url=http://movieweb.com/movie/oceans-thirteen/george-clooney-and-matt-damon-interview/ |website=movieweb.com |accessdate=September 19, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921020555/http://movieweb.com/movie/oceans-thirteen/george-clooney-and-matt-damon-interview/ |archive-date=September 21, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, Clooney and Soderbergh co-founded [[Section Eight Productions]], for which [[Grant Heslov]] was president of television. Clooney made his directorial debut in the 2002 film ''[[Confessions of a Dangerous Mind (film)|Confessions of a Dangerous Mind]]'', based on the autobiography of TV producer [[Chuck Barris]]. Though the film did not do well at the box office, critics stated that Clooney's directing showed promise.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jackasscritics.com/movie.php?movie_key=275 |title=Jackass Critics \u2013 Confessions of a Dangerous Mind |publisher=Jack Ass Critics |accessdate=June 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Clooney starred in ''[[Syriana]]'', which was based loosely on former [[Central Intelligence Agency]] agent [[Robert Baer]]'s memoirs of his service in the Middle East. Clooney suffered an accident on the set of ''Syriana'', which caused a brain injury with complications from a punctured [[dura mater|dura]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.contactmusic.com/new/xmlfeed.nsf/mndwebpages/clooney%20contemplated%20suicide%20over%20brain%20injury |title=George Clooney \u2013 Clooney Contemplated Suicide Over Brain Injury |publisher=Contact Music |accessdate=September 19, 2009 |date=October 23, 2005}}</ref> The same year he directed, produced, and starred in ''[[Good Night, and Good Luck]]'', a film about 1950s television journalist [[Edward R. Murrow]]'s famous war of words with Senator [[Joseph McCarthy]]. At the 2006 Academy Awards, Clooney was nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]] and [[Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay|Best Original Screenplay]] for ''Good Night, and Good Luck'', as well as [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for ''Syriana''. He won the Oscar for his role in ''Syriana''.<ref>{{cite news |title=George Clooney Wins Supporting Actor: 2006 Oscars |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NqDbG9h-f7c |accessdate=September 19, 2015 |website=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:George Clooney-4 The Men Who Stare at Goats TIFF09 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|George Clooney at the premiere of ''[[The Men Who Stare at Goats (film)|The Men Who Stare at Goats]]'' in the [[2009 Toronto International Film Festival]]]]\n\nClooney next appeared in ''[[The Good German]]'' (2006), a [[film noir]] directed by Soderbergh that is set in post-World War II Germany. In August 2006, Clooney and Heslov started the production company [[Smokehouse Pictures]]. In October 2006, Clooney received the [[American Cinematheque Award]], which honors someone in the entertainment industry who has made \"a significant contribution to the art of motion pictures\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.americancinematheque.com/ball/2006/2006georgeclooney.htm |title=The Presentation of the 21st Annual American Cinematheque Award. |accessdate=September 27, 2014}}</ref> On January 22, 2008, Clooney was nominated for an Academy Award for Best Actor for ''[[Michael Clayton (film)|Michael Clayton]]'' (2007) but did not win. Later that year, he directed his third film, ''[[Leatherheads]]'', in which he also starred. On April 4, 2008, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' reported that Clooney had quietly resigned from the [[Writers Guild of America]] over a dispute concerning ''[[Leatherheads]]''. Clooney, who is the director, producer, and star of the film, claimed that he had contributed in writing \"all but two scenes\" of it, and requested a writing credit alongside Duncan Brantley and [[Rick Reilly]], who had worked on the screenplay for 17 years. Clooney lost an arbitration vote 2\u20131, and withdrew from the union over the decision. He became a \"[[financial core]] status\" non-member, meaning he no longer has voting rights, and cannot run for office or attend membership meetings, according to the WGA's constitution.<ref name=\"reuters1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSN0239381220080404 |title=George Clooney in feud with writers union |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=February 9, 2009 |accessdate=September 19, 2009}}</ref>\n\nHe next co-starred with [[Ewan McGregor]] and [[Kevin Spacey]] in the war comedy film ''[[The Men Who Stare at Goats (film)|The Men Who Stare at Goats]]'', which was directed by Heslov and released in November 2009. Also in November 2009, he voiced the title character in [[Wes Anderson]]'s [[animated feature]] ''[[Fantastic Mr. Fox (film)|Fantastic Mr. Fox]]''. The same year, Clooney starred in the comedy-drama ''[[Up in the Air (2009 film)|Up in the Air]]'', which was initially given limited release, and then wide-released on December 25, 2009. For his performance in the film, which was directed by [[Jason Reitman]], he was nominated for a [[Golden Globe]], a [[Screen Actors Guild Award]], [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA]], and an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]].<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1193138/awards ''Up in the Air (I) (2009): Awards'', IMDb, Undated]. Retrieved August 7, 2015.</ref> 2010 saw the release of ''[[The American (2010 film)|The American]]'', based on the novel ''[[A Very Private Gentleman]]'' by [[Martin Booth]] and directed by [[Anton Corbijn]]. Clooney played the lead role, and was a producer of the film.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1440728/fullcredits ''The American (2010): Full Cast & CrewIMDb, Undated]. Retrieved August 7, 2015.</ref>\n\n===2011\u2013present===\n{{as of|2011}}, Clooney is represented by [[Bryan Lourd]], co-chairman of [[Creative Artists Agency]] (CAA).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://famous-relationships.topsynergy.com/George_Clooney/Contact.asp |title=George Clooney contact information |publisher=Top Synergy |accessdate=June 17, 2012}}</ref> In 2011 Clooney starred in ''[[The Descendants]]'' as a husband whose wife has an accident that leaves her in a coma. He earned critical praise for his work, and won the [[Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Actor]] and the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Drama]]. Also, he was nominated for the [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Leading Role|Screen Actors Guild for Best Actor]], the [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor]], and the [[Academy Award for Best Actor]]. He was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Adapted Screenplay]] for the political drama ''[[The Ides of March (2011 film)|The Ides of March]]''.\nIn 2013, Clooney won the [[Golden Globe for Best Motion Picture - Drama]], the [[BAFTA Award for Best Picture]] and the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]] for producing ''[[Argo (2012 film)|Argo]]''. He is the only person in Academy Award history to be nominated for Oscars in six different categories: Best Picture, Best Actor, Best Supporting Actor, Best Director, Best Original Screenplay and Best Adapted Screenplay.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1124035/awards ''The Ides of March (2011): Awards'', IMDb, Undated]. Retrieved August 7, 2015.</ref>\n\nClooney co-starred with [[Sandra Bullock]] in ''[[Gravity (2013 film)|Gravity]]'' (2013), a space thriller directed by [[Alfonso Cuar\u00f3n]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/01/gravity-movie-sandra-bullock-release-date-october-4-2013-announced/ |magazine=Deadline.com |title=Warner Bros Dates Sandra Bullock Pic 'Gravity' \u2013 Again |date=January 15, 2013 |accessdate=May 15, 2013}}</ref> He co-wrote, directed and starred in ''[[The Monuments Men]]'', an adaption of ''The Monuments Men: Allied Heroes, Nazi Thieves and the Greatest Treasure Hunt in History'' by [[Robert M. Edsel]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.deadline.com/2012/12/matt-damon-joins-monumental-cast-of-george-clooneys-next-film/ |magazine=Deadline.com |title=Matt Damon in Talks To Join Monumental Cast of George Clooney's Next Film |date=December 4, 2012 |accessdate=May 15, 2013 |last=Fleming Jr |first=Mike}}</ref> Clooney also produced ''[[August: Osage County (film)|August: Osage County]]'' (2013), an adaptation of [[August: Osage County|the play of the same name]]. The film stars [[Meryl Streep]] and [[Julia Roberts]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.deadline.com/2012/06/smokehouses-george-clooney-and-grant-heslov-producing-august-osage-county/ |title=Smokehouse's George Clooney And Grant Heslov Producing 'August: Osage County' |magazine=Deadline.com |date=June 18, 2012 |accessdate=May 15, 2013}}</ref> His next film was ''[[Tomorrowland (film)|Tomorrowland]]'' (2015), a science fiction adventure film in which he played Frank Walker, an inventor.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ito |first1=Robert |title=Going Back to the Future for 'Tomorrowland,' From Disney |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/17/movies/going-back-to-the-future-for-tomorrowland-from-disney.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=May 16, 2016 |date=May 14, 2015}}</ref> Later in the year, he was featured as himself in the [[Netflix]] Christmas musical comedy ''[[A Very Murray Christmas]]'', starring [[Bill Murray]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Spangler |first1=Todd |title=Bill Murray Christmas Special Coming to Netflix |url=https://variety.com/2015/digital/news/bill-murray-netflix-christmas-special-1201503528/ |accessdate=May 16, 2016 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=May 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''[[Hail, Caesar!]]'', a comedy from the Coen brothers set in the Hollywood film industry in the 1950s, premiered in February 2016. Clooney portrayed Baird Whitlock, a [[Robert Taylor (actor)|Robert Taylor]]-type film star who is kidnapped during the production of a film. [[Josh Brolin]] co-starred as [[Cleaner (crime)|fixer]] [[Eddie Mannix]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Collin |first1=Robbie |title=The Coen Brothers: 'We get you invested, then shake the floor' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/film/hail-caesar/coen-brothers-interview/ |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |accessdate=May 16, 2016 |date=February 26, 2016}}</ref> Clooney reunited with [[Julia Roberts]] for the [[Jodie Foster]]-directed thriller ''[[Money Monster]]'' (2016), playing the host of a television show that investigates conspiracies on [[commerce]] and [[Wall Street]], who is taken hostage by a bankrupt viewer given a bad tip.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Puchko |first1=Kristy |title=George Clooney's New Movie Money Monster Has A Stacked Cast |url=http://www.cinemablend.com/new/George-Clooney-Movie-Money-Monster-Has-Stacked-Cast-68249.html |website=Cinemablend |date=November 17, 2014 |accessdate=May 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Clooney co-founded [[Casamigos]] Tequila with [[Rande Gerber]] and Michael Meldman.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/06/21/george-clooney-accidentally-started-a-tequila-company-worth-1-billion.html |title=How George Clooney accidentally started a tequila company that's too successful to stop |last=Elkins |first=Kathleen |date=November 2, 2016 |publisher=}}</ref> It was sold to [[Diageo]] for $700 million in June 2017, with an additional $300 million possible depending on the company's performance over the next ten years.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/06/21/george-clooney-just-sold-his-tequila-business-for-1-billion.html |title=George Clooney just sold his tequila business for up to $1 billion |last=Whitten |first=Sarah |date=June 21, 2017 |publisher=}}</ref> According to ''[[Forbes]]'' annual ranking, he was the world's highest-paid actor for 2017-2018, earning $239 million between June 1, 2017 and June 1, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/natalierobehmed/2018/08/22/the-worlds-highest-paid-actors-2018-george-clooney-tops-list-with-239-million |title=The World's Highest-Paid Actors 2018: George Clooney Tops List With $239 Million |last=Robehmed |first=Natalie |date=August 22, 2018 |work=[[Forbes]] |accessdate=August 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017 his directorial project ''[[Suburbicon]]'' a 1950s-set crime comedy was released. It stars [[Matt Damon]], [[Julianne Moore]], and [[Oscar Isaac]], from a script written by the Coen brothers in the 1980s, that they had originally intended to direct themselves.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nugent |first1=John |title=Woody Harrelson joins the cast of George Clooney's Suburbicon |url=http://www.empireonline.com/people/george-clooney/woody-harrelson-george-clooney-suburbicon/ |website=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |accessdate=May 19, 2016 |date=May 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe received the 2018 AFI Life Achievement Award on June 7, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.afi.com/george-clooney-to-receive-46th-afi-life-achievement-award/ |title=George Clooney to Receive 46th AFI Life Achievement Award |publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Activism and public advocacy==\n\n===Political views===\nClooney is a supporter of [[LGBT social movements|gay rights]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.entertainmentwise.com/news/70771/George-Clooney-Doesnt-Give-A-St-If-People-Think-He-Is-Gay- |title=George Clooney Doesn't 'Give A S**t' If People Think He Is Gay |work=EntertainmentWise |accessdate=September 27, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141001030525/http://www.entertainmentwise.com/news/70771/George-Clooney-Doesnt-Give-A-St-If-People-Think-He-Is-Gay- |archivedate=October 1, 2014 |df=}}</ref> He supported both of [[Barack Obama]]'s [[Barack Obama 2008 presidential campaign|2008]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywood.com/news/detail/id/3570488 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061106043604/http://www.hollywood.com/news/detail/id/3570488 |archivedate=November 6, 2006 |title=Clooney Welcomes Obama's Presidential Bid |date=October 25, 2006 |work=Hollywood.com}}</ref> and [[Barack Obama 2012 presidential campaign|2012]] presidential campaigns.<ref name=\"hollywooddonors\">(2011-07-16) {{cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0711/59184.html |title=Hollywood stars open wallets for Obama |accessdate=January 23, 2013}}</ref> Clooney endorsed [[Hillary Clinton]] for the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Boucher |first=Philip |title=Tom Hanks Predicts Donald Trump Will Become President When 'Spaceships Come Down Filled With Dinosaurs' |date=April 26, 2016 |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |url=http://www.people.com/article/tom-hanks-donald-trump-presidency-spaceship-filled-with-dinosaurs |accessdate=July 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Humanitarian work===\n[[File:George Clooney with Samoura and Reck.JPG|thumb|Clooney in [[Ab\u00e9ch\u00e9]], Chad, in January 2008 with the U.N]]\nClooney is involved with [[Not On Our Watch Project]], an organization that focuses global attention and resources to stop and prevent mass atrocities, along with [[Brad Pitt]], [[Matt Damon]], [[Don Cheadle]], [[David Pressman]], and [[Jerry Weintraub]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://notonourwatchproject.org/ |title=Not on Our Watch Project |publisher=Not on Our Watch Project |date=August 11, 2009 |accessdate=September 19, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070512213019/http://www.notonourwatchproject.org/ |archive-date=May 12, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In February 2009, he visited Goz Beida, Chad, with ''[[New York Times]]'' columnist [[Nicholas D. Kristof]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Sisters, Victims, Heroes |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/22/opinion/22kristof.html |work=The New York Times |first=Nicholas |last=Kristof |date=February 21, 2009 |accessdate=May 3, 2010}}</ref> In January 2010, he organized the telethon ''[[Hope for Haiti Now: A Global Benefit for Earthquake Relief|Hope for Haiti Now]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.de/news/2010-01-22/21054242-george-clooney-hope-for-haiti-wird-gross.html |title=George Clooney: \"'Hope For Haiti' wird gro\u00df!\" |publisher=MTV |date=January 22, 2010 |language=de |accessdate=January 23, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100125145510/http://www.mtv.de/news/2010-01-22/21054242-george-clooney-hope-for-haiti-wird-gross.html |archivedate=January 25, 2010}}</ref> which collected donations for the [[2010 Haiti earthquake]] victims.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/SHOWBIZ/TV/01/22/haiti.telethon/index.html |title=Telethon tries to raise 'Hope for Haiti' - CNN.com |website=www.cnn.com}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2012, Clooney starred with [[Martin Sheen]] and [[Brad Pitt]] in a performance of [[Dustin Lance Black]]'s play, ''[[8 (play)|'8']]''\u2014a staged reenactment of the [[Perry v. Brown|federal trial]] that overturned California's [[California Proposition 8|Prop 8 ban]] on [[Same-sex marriage in California|same-sex marriage]]\u2014as attorney [[David Boies]].<ref name=\"8 the play\">{{cite news |title=George Clooney, Brad Pitt lead all-star Prop. 8 play reading |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/culturemonster/2012/03/george-clooney-brad-pitt-enact-prop-8-stage-drama.html |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=March 18, 2012 |date=March 4, 2012}}</ref> The production was held at the [[Wilshire Ebell Theatre]] and broadcast on [[YouTube]] to raise money for the [[American Foundation for Equal Rights]].<ref name=\"8 play video\">{{cite web |title=\"8\": A Play about the Fight for Marriage Equality |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qlUG8F9uVgM |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=March 18, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=YouTube to broadcast Proposition 8 play live |url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2012/03/01/youtube-to-broadcast-proposition-8-play-live/ |publisher=pinknews.co.uk |accessdate=March 18, 2012}}</ref> In September 2012, Clooney offered to take an auction winner out to lunch to benefit the Gay, Lesbian and Straight Education Network (GLSEN). GLSEN works to create a safe space in schools for children who are or may be perceived to be gay, lesbian, bisexual or transgender.<ref>{{cite web |title=George Clooney, Neil Patrick Harris Participate in Gay Youth Charity Auction |url=http://www.ontopmag.com/article.aspx?id=13066&MediaType=1&Category=22 |publisher=On Top Magazine |accessdate=September 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Darfur===\n[[File:George Clooney - White House - October 2010 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Clooney discusses Sudan with President [[Barack Obama]] at the White House in October 2010.]]\nClooney has advocated a resolution of the [[Darfur conflict]].<ref>[http://people.monstersandcritics.com/news/article_1315091.php/George_Clooneys_Sudan_help George Clooney's Sudan help] June 7, 2007. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080315035228/http://people.monstersandcritics.com/news/article_1315091.php/George_Clooneys_Sudan_help |date=March 15, 2008 }}</ref> He spoke at a 2006 [[Save Darfur Coalition|Save Darfur]] rally in [[Washington, D.C.]] In April 2006, he spent ten days in Chad and Sudan with his father to make the TV special \"A Journey to Darfur\" reflecting the situation of Darfur's refugees, and advocated for action. The documentary was broadcast on American cable TV as well as in the UK and France. In 2008, it was released on DVD with the sale proceeds being donated to the [[International Rescue Committee]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117966145.html?categoryid=2522&cs=1 |title=American Life TV targets baby boomers: Channel airing Clooney's Darfur docu |date=June 1, 2007 |work=Variety |accessdate=September 27, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Stein |first=Joel |url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/2007/time100/article/0,28804,1595326_1615754_1615880,00.html |title=The Time 100: George Clooney |work=Time |date=September 14, 2009 |accessdate=September 19, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504110103/http://www.time.com/time/specials/2007/time100/article/0%2C28804%2C1595326_1615754_1615880%2C00.html |archivedate=May 4, 2009 |df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2007/01/11/ap/entertainment/mainD8MJ771O0.shtml |title=Clooney's Docu on Darfur to Air Monday |accessdate=November 1, 2008 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081101030249/http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2007/01/11/ap/entertainment/mainD8MJ771O0.shtml |archivedate=November 1, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.marketwire.com/press-release/Americanlife-Tv-838350.html |title=AmericanLife TV Network (ALN) Donates Proceeds From \"A Journey to Darfur\" DVD to the International Rescue Committee |accessdate=January 13, 2009 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090113181149/http://www.marketwire.com/press-release/Americanlife-Tv-838350.html |archivedate=January 13, 2009}} \"In addition to premiering on AmericanLife TV Network, \"A Journey to Darfur\" has aired on The Community Channel in England and France 2. The documentary has also been shown at festivals and schools around the world, including, The second Refugee Film Festival in Tokyo presented by the UNHCR, Ilaria Alpi Journalistic Television Award based in Riccione, Italy, Milano Doc Festival, and the Human Rights Nights Film Festival in Bologna, Italy.\"</ref> In September of the same year, he spoke to the UN Security Council with Nobel Prize-winner [[Elie Wiesel]] to ask the UN to find a solution to the conflict and to help the people of Darfur.<ref>Linton, Leyla. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/09/15/AR2006091500507.html Clooney urges UN action on Darfur] ''The Washington Post''. September 15, 2006.</ref> In December, he visited China and Egypt with Don Cheadle and two Olympic winners to ask both governments to pressure Sudan's government.<ref>Friedman, Roger. [http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,235977,00.html George Clooney's Secret Mission] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071104135031/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,235977,00.html |date=November 4, 2007 }} Fox News Channel. December 12, 2006.</ref>\n\nOn March 25, 2007, he sent an open letter to German Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]], calling on the [[European Union]] to take \"decisive action\" in the region given the failure of Sudan President [[Omar al-Bashir]] to respond to UN resolutions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Europe calls on Sudan to accept UN resolution |url=http://www.sudantribune.com/spip.php?page=imprimable&id_article=20965 |work=Sudan Tribune |accessdate=April 28, 2014 |date=March 25, 2007}}</ref> He narrated and was co-executive producer of the 2007 documentary ''[[Sand and Sorrow]]''.<ref>Weissberg, Jay. [http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117933979.html?categoryid=31&cs=1 Sand and Sorrow review]. ''Variety''. June 25, 2007.</ref> Clooney also appeared in the documentary film ''[[Darfur Now]]'', a call-to-action film released in November 2007 for people all over the world to help stop the Darfur crisis.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20041022000341/http://www.hopeforhaitinow.org/ Hope For Haiti Now: A Global Benefit For Earthquake Relief].</ref> In December 2007, Clooney and fellow actor Don Cheadle received the Summit Peace Award from the Nobel Peace Prize Laureates in Rome. In his acceptance speech, Clooney said that \"Don and I ... stand here before you as failures. The simple truth is that when it comes to the atrocities in Darfur ... those people are not better off now than they were years ago.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Clooney and Cheadle Honored by Nobel Prize Winners |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20162577,00.html |work=People |first=Scott |last=Huver |date=November 26, 2007}}</ref> On January 18, 2008, the United Nations announced Clooney's appointment as a UN messenger of peace, effective January 31.<ref name=peace /><ref name=bbc1 />\n\nClooney conceived of and, with [[John Prendergast (activist)|John Prendergast]] \u2013 human rights activist, co-founder of the [[Enough Project]], and Strategic Advisor for Not on Our Watch Project \u2013 initiated the [[Satellite Sentinel Project]] (SSP), after an October 2010 trip to [[South Sudan]]. SSP aims to monitor armed activity for signs of renewed civil war between [[Sudan]] and South Sudan, and to detect and deter mass atrocities along the border regions there.<ref>{{cite news |title=George Clooney speaks to CLSA clients |url=http://www.indiainfoline.com/Markets/News/George-Clooney-speaks-to-CLSA-clients/5247997370 |agency=India Infoline News Service |date=September 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\nClooney and [[John Prendergast (activist)|John Prendergast]] co-wrote a ''[[Washington Post]]'' op-ed piece in May 2011, titled \"Dancing with a dictator in Sudan\", arguing that:\n\n{{quote|President Omar al-Bashir has been indicted by the [[International Criminal Court]] for [[genocide]], is escalating bombing and food aid obstruction in Darfur, and he now threatens the entire north-south peace process ... the evidence shows that incentives alone are insufficient to change [[Khartoum]]'s calculations. International support should be sought immediately for denying [[debt relief]], expanding the ICC indictments, diplomatically isolating the regime, suspending all non-humanitarian aid, obstructing state-controlled bank transactions and freezing accounts holding oil wealth diverted by senior regime officials.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/dancing-with-a-dictator-in-sudan/2011/05/27/AGYMCzCH_story.html |work=The Washington Post |first=Stephen F. |last=Hayes |title=Dancing with a dictator in Sudan |date=May 27, 2011}}</ref>}}\n\nOn March 16, 2012, Clooney was arrested outside the Sudanese Embassy for [[civil disobedience]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-17403715 |work=BBC News |title=George Clooney released after Sudan embassy arrest |date=March 16, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian-arrest\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/mar/16/george-clooney-arrested-sudanese-embassy |title=George Clooney arrested in planned protest at Sudanese embassy |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=March 16, 2012 |first=Ryan |last=Devereaux}}</ref> He intended to be arrested when he planned the protest.<ref name=\"guardian-arrest\" /> Several other prominent participants were also arrested, including [[Martin Luther King III]].<ref name=\"guardian-arrest\" /> Clooney has been described as one of the most strident critics of Omar al-Bashir.<ref>{{cite news |title=Donald Trump ducks a decision on sanctions on Khartoum |url=https://www.economist.com/news/middle-east-and-africa/21724999-faced-complex-choice-about-unfamiliar-country-president |accessdate=July 15, 2017 |work=[[The Economist]] |date=July 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Armenian Genocide===\nClooney supports the recognition of the [[Armenian Genocide]]. He is one of the chief associates of the 100 Lives Initiative, a project which aims to remember the lives lost during the event.<ref name=huffpost>{{cite news |last1=Sieczkowski |first1=Cavan |title=George And Amal Clooney Attend '100 Lives' Commemoration |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/03/11/george-clooney-amal-clooney-100-lives_n_6846536.html |agency=Huffington Post |date=March 11, 2015}}</ref> As part of the initiative, Clooney launched the [[Aurora Prize]], which awards to those who risk their lives to prevent genocides and atrocities.<ref name=huffpost /><ref name=asbarez>{{cite news |title='There was a genocide of Armenians in 1915,' Says George Clooney |url=http://asbarez.com/141109/there-was-a-genocide-of-armenians-in-1915-says-george-clooney/ |agency=Asbarez |date=October 27, 2015}}</ref> Clooney had also urged various American government officials to support the United States' recognition of the Armenian Genocide.<ref name=asbarez /> Clooney visited Armenia to commemorate the 101st anniversary of the event in April 2016.<ref>{{cite news |title=George and Amal Clooney to visit Armenia next year |url=http://www.panarmenian.net/eng/news/199686/ |agency=PanArmenian |date=October 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Syria===\nIn May 2015, Clooney told the [[BBC]] that the Syrian conflict was too complicated politically to get involved in and he wanted to focus on helping the refugees.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-32791065 |title=George Clooney: Syria conflict 'incredibly complex' \u2013 BBC News |website=BBC News |language=en-GB|access-date=April 29, 2016}}</ref> In March 2016, he and his wife, Amal Clooney, met with Syrian refugees living in Berlin to mark the fifth anniversary of the conflict, before meeting with German Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]] to thank her for Germany's open-door policy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/amal-clooney-and-george-clooney-meet-with-refugees-to-mark-fifth-anniversary-of-syrian-crisis-a6934041.html |title=Amal Clooney tells refugees how her family were once forced to flee their homeland too |date=March 16, 2016 |website=The Independent |language=en-GB|access-date=April 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Gun control===\nIn 2018, following the [[Stoneman Douglas High School shooting]], the Clooneys pledged $500,000 to the [[March for Our Lives]] and said they would be in attendance.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/the-wrap/article/George-and-Amal-Clooney-Donate-500-000-for-12626898.php |title=Oprah Follows George and Amal Clooney's Lead, to Donate $500,000 for Parkland Students' March |date=February 20, 2018 |publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===LGBT rights===\nOn March 28, 2019, Clooney wrote an open letter calling for the boycott of the Sultan of Brunei's hotels over a new law that came into force on April 3, 2019 that punishes homosexual sex and adultery with death by stoning. Clooney lists 9 hotels including [[The Dorchester]], 45 Park Lane, [[Coworth Park]], [[The Beverly Hills Hotel]], [[Hotel Bel-Air]], [[Le Meurice]], [[Hotel Plaza Athenee]], Hotel Eden and Hotel Principe di Savoia and asks readers to consider how \"we are putting money directly into the pockets of men who choose to stone and whip to death their own citizens for being gay or accused of adultery.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Brunei to punish gay sex and adultery with death by stoning |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/03/27/asia/brunei-anti-lgbt-stoning-law-intl/index.html |accessdate=March 29, 2019 |publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Clooney |first1=George |title=George Clooney: Boycott Sultan Of Brunei's Hotels Over Cruel Anti-Gay Laws |url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/george-clooney-sultain-of-brunei-hotels-boycott-beverly-hills-hotel-anti-gay-laws-brunei-1202584579/ |magazine=Deadline Hollywood |date=March 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\n===Relationships===\n[[File:George Clooney and Amal Clooney - Berlin Berlinale 66 (24977282895) (cropped).jpg|thumb|Clooney and [[Amal Clooney|Alamuddin]] at the 66th Berlin International Film Festival in Germany in 2016]]\n\nClooney dated actress [[Kelly Preston]] (1987\u20131989). Clooney was married to actress [[Talia Balsam]] from 1989 to 1993.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/talia-balsam-divorce-actress-on-being-married-to-george-clooney-a7350041.html |title=Talia Balsam, Divorce actress, on being married to George Clooney: 'I should not have been married at that point' |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=October 7, 2016 |last=Saul |first=Heather}}</ref> He also had a relationship with actress [[Ginger Lynn Allen]].  Clooney dated French [[La Ferme C\u00e9l\u00e9brit\u00e9s (series 1)|reality TV personality]] C\u00e9line Balitran (1996\u20131999).<ref>{{cite web |author=George Clooney |url=http://www.people.com/people/george_clooney/biography |title=George Clooney Biography |work=People |accessdate=June 17, 2012}}</ref> After meeting British model [[Lisa Snowdon]] in 2000, he had a five-year [[on-again, off-again relationship]] with her.<ref>{{cite news |last=Walker |first=Tim |title=Lisa Snowdon says George Clooney is no Mr Right |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mandrake/5259228/Lisa-Snowdon-says-George-Clooney-is-no-Mr-Right.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=April 16, 2014 |date=May 1, 2009 |location=London}}</ref>\nClooney dated [[Ren\u00e9e Zellweger]] (2001) and [[Krista Allen]] (2002\u20132008).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,443521,00.html |publisher=Fox News Channel |title=Report: George Clooney Rekindles Romance With Krista Allen |date=December 1, 2011}}</ref> In June 2007, he started dating [[reality television|reality personality]] Sarah Larson, but the couple broke up in May 2008.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20202854,00.html |title=George Clooney and Sarah Larson split |work=People |date=May 28, 2008}}</ref> In July 2009, Clooney was in a relationship with Italian actress [[Elisabetta Canalis]] until they split in June 2011.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Who Is George Clooney's New Italian Girl? |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20294758,00.html |journal=People |date=July 30, 2009 |author=Simon Perry}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20504498,00.html |title=George Clooney and Elisabetta Canalis Split |journal=People |date=June 22, 2011 |author=Elizabeth Leonard}}</ref> In July 2011, Clooney started dating former [[WWE]] personnel [[Stacy Keibler]],<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20526285,00.html |title=George Clooney and Stacy Keibler Are Still Dating |journal=People |author=Michelle Tauber |date=September 7, 2011}}</ref> and they ended their relationship in July 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.accesshollywood.com/george-clooney-and-stacy-keibler-split-had-nothing-to-do-with-kids-marriage_article_81608 |title=George Clooney & Stacy Keibler Split; Had 'Nothing To Do' With Kids, Marriage |work=Access Hollywood |accessdate=September 27, 2014}}</ref>\n\nClooney became engaged to British-Lebanese human rights lawyer [[Amal Clooney|Amal Alamuddin]] on April 28, 2014.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Padraic Flanagan |title=George Clooney engaged to 'utterly wonderful' British lawyer |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/10792847/George-Clooney-engaged-to-utterly-wonderful-British-lawyer.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=June 8, 2014 |date=April 28, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=April 28, 2014 |url=http://www.startribune.com/entertainment/movies/257006381.html |author=Jill Lawless |title=George Clooney engaged to UK attorney Amal Alamuddin, her law firm says as it offers congrats |newspaper=[[Star Tribune]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=May 11, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140511164941/http://www.startribune.com/entertainment/movies/257006381.html |url-status=dead |archivedate=May 11, 2014}}</ref> In July 2014, Clooney publicly mocked the British tabloid newspaper the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' after it claimed his fianc\u00e9e's mother opposes their marriage on religious grounds.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-28225467 |title=George Clooney slams Daily Mail over 'irresponsible' marriage story |work=BBC News |accessdate=September 27, 2014}}</ref> When the tabloid apologized for its false story, Clooney refused to accept the apology. He called the paper \"the worst kind of tabloid. One that makes up its facts to the detriment of its readers.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-28262019 |title=George Clooney rejects Mail Online apology |date=July 11, 2014 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=July 11, 2014}}</ref> On August 7, 2014, Clooney and Alamuddin obtained marriage licenses at the [[Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea]] of the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/george-clooney-fiance-amal-alamuddin-marriage-license/story?id=24877642 |publisher=ABC News |title=George Clooney and Fianc\u00e9e Amal Alamuddin Get Marriage License |author=Michael Rothman |date=August 7, 2014 |accessdate=August 8, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808021953/http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/george-clooney-fiance-amal-alamuddin-marriage-license/story?id=24877642 |archivedate=August 8, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> Alamuddin and Clooney were officially married on September 27, 2014, at [[Ca' Farsetti]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Kington |first=Tom |title=George Clooney Marries in Venice Ceremony |url=http://news.sky.com/story/1343410/george-clooney-marries-in-venice-ceremony |accessdate=September 27, 2014 |publisher=Sky News |date=September 27, 2014}}</ref> They were married by Clooney's friend [[Walter Veltroni]], the former mayor of [[Rome]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/italy/11097278/George-Clooney-to-be-married-by-ex-Rome-mayor.html |title=George Clooney 'to be married by ex-Rome mayor' |work=The Telegraph |date=September 15, 2014 |first=Nick |last=Squires |accessdate=September 27, 2014}}</ref>\nIn 2015, Clooney and Alamuddin adopted a rescue dog, a bassett hound named Millie, from the San Gabriel Valley Humane Society.<ref>{{cite web |title=George Clooney, Wife Adopt Basset Hound Mix Named Millie From Shelter |url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2015/10/29/george-clooney-wife-adopt-basset-hound-named-millie/ |website=CBS News |accessdate=October 30, 2015}}</ref>\nOn February 9, 2017, it was reported by the CBS talk show, ''[[The Talk (TV series)|The Talk]]'', that Amal was pregnant, and that they were expecting twins.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-38926056 |title=George and Amal Clooney 'expecting twins', Matt Damon confirms |publisher=BBC |date=February 10, 2017 |accessdate=March 5, 2017}}</ref> On June 6, 2017, Amal gave birth to a daughter, Ella, and a son, Alexander.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://people.com/babies/george-clooney-amal-clooney-welcome-twins/ |title=George and Amal Clooney Welcome Son Alexander and Daughter Ella |date=June 6, 2017 |publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Real estate===\nClooney has property in [[Los Angeles]]. He purchased the {{convert|7354|ft2|m2|adj=on}} house in 1995 through his George Guilfoyle Trust. His home in [[Italy]] is in the village of [[Laglio]], on [[Lake Como]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.news.com.au/clooney-at-home-in-italy/story-e6frfmwr-1111114634930 |title=Clooney at home in Italy |publisher=News.com |date=October 14, 2007 |accessdate=May 25, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100503171909/http://www.news.com.au/clooney-at-home-in-italy/story-e6frfmwr-1111114634930 |archivedate=May 3, 2010}}</ref> near the former residence of Italian author [[Ada Negri]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Villa Negri \u2013 Location |url=http://www.villa-negri.com/location/ |publisher=Villa Negri |accessdate=April 28, 2014}}</ref> Clooney also owns a home in [[Los Cabos]], [[Mexico]], that is next door to the home of [[Cindy Crawford]] and [[Rande Gerber]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.architecturaldigest.com/celebrity-homes/2013/george-clooney-cindy-crawford-rande-gerber-mexico-baja-houses-article |title=Cindy Crawford and Rande Gerber and George Clooney's Side-By-Side Mexican Villas |work=Architectural Digest |accessdate=September 27, 2014}}</ref> In 2014, Clooney and his new British wife Amal Alamuddin bought the Grade II [[Listed building|listed]]{{Lbe|1047410|note=Listed building}} Mill House on an island in the [[River Thames]] at [[Sonning Eye]] in [[Oxfordshire]], [[England]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mylusciouslife.com/george-and-amal-clooney-island-mill-house-in-sonning-eye-outside-london/ |title=Clooney's Mill House in Sonning Eye, Oxfordshire |newspaper=[[MyLusciousLife.com]] |first=Natasha |last=Wood |date=October 16, 2014 |accessdate=October 16, 2014}}</ref> at a cost of around [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]10&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/11152701/George-Clooney-snaps-up-10-million-manor-house-in-Sonning-Berkshire.html |title=George Clooney snaps up \u00a310&nbsp;million manor house in Sonning, Berkshire |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |first=Patrick |last=Sawer |date=October 9, 2014 |accessdate=October 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Motorcycle accidents===\nOn September 21, 2007, Clooney and then-girlfriend Sarah Larson were injured in a motorcycle accident in [[Weehawken, New Jersey]], when his motorcycle was hit by a car. The driver of the car reported that Clooney attempted to pass him on the right,<ref>McDonald, Ray.{{cite web |url=http://voanews.com/english/Entertainment/2007-09-24-voa41.cfm?renderforprint=1&textonly=1&&CFID=126093321&CFTOKEN=52082908 |title=Actor George Clooney Injured in Motorcycle Accident |accessdate=December 13, 2013 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012003506/http://voanews.com/english/Entertainment/2007-09-24-voa41.cfm?renderforprint=1&textonly=1&&CFID=126093321&CFTOKEN=52082908 |archivedate=October 12, 2007}}, Voice of America, September 24, 2007.</ref> while Clooney said that the driver signaled left and then decided to make an abrupt right turn and clipped his motorcycle. On October 9, 2007, more than two dozen staff at [[Palisades Medical Center]] were suspended without pay for looking at Clooney's medical records in violation of federal law.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory?id=3710823 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012034258/http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory?id=3710823 |archivedate=October 12, 2007 |title=Hospital Staffers Suspended Over Clooney |publisher=ABC News |date=October 10, 2007 |first=North |last=Bergen}}</ref>\n\nOn July 10, 2018, Clooney was hit by a car while riding a motorcycle to a film set in [[Sardinia]]. He was hospitalized with minor, non-life-threatening injuries.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.sky.com/story/george-clooney-injured-in-car-accident-reports-11431777 |title=George Clooney 'injured in motorbike accident' in Sardinia |work=Sky News|access-date=July 10, 2018 |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jul/10/george-clooney-reportedly-injured-after-motorbike-crash-in-sardinia |title=George Clooney reportedly injured after motorbike crash in Sardinia |work=The Guardian|access-date=July 10, 2018 |date=July 10, 2018 |publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\nGrowing up around Cincinnati, Clooney is a fan of the [[Cincinnati Bengals]] and [[Cincinnati Reds]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/353674/george-clooney-s-cincinnati-bengals-tee-is-having-a-moment |title=George Clooney's Bengals Tee Is Having a Moment |publisher=}}</ref> He tried out to be a Red in 1977.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.mlb.com/cutfour/2015/05/06/122710430/did-you-know-that-george-clooney-tried-out-for-the-reds-in-1977 |title=Did you know that George Clooney tried out for the Reds in 1977? |website=Major League Baseball}}</ref>\n\n==In the media==\nClooney has appeared in commercials outside the U.S. for [[Fiat]], [[Nespresso]], [[Martini vermouth]], and [[Omega SA|Omega]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DoapqteSo8Q |title=OMEGA in Space: George Clooney's story |last=OMEGA |date=January 23, 2017 |publisher= |via=YouTube}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=George Clooney \u2013 Fiat IDEA \u2013 Auto commercial |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6ZtWYOymFgc |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=April 28, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=George Clooney tastes sustainability in Nespresso coffee |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/blog/2013/jul/17/george-clooney-nespresso-coffee-ad |work=The Guardian |author=Lucy Siegle |date=July 17, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=George Clooney to star in new Martini ad |url=http://www.healthclubmanagement.co.uk/detail.cfm?Pagetype=detail&subject=product&codeID=9485 |publisher=Health Club Management |accessdate=April 28, 2014 |date=October 29, 2004}}</ref> Clooney was named one of ''Time'' magazine's 100 Most Influential People in the World in 2007, 2008, and 2009.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1894410_1894289_1894280,00.html |work=Time |title=The 2009 Time 100 |date=April 30, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130826200952/http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0%2C28804%2C1894410_1894289_1894280%2C00.html |archivedate=August 26, 2013 |df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/2007/article/0,28804,1595326_1615754_1615880,00.html |work=Time |title=The Time 100 |date=May 3, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824170958/http://www.time.com/time/specials/2007/article/0%2C28804%2C1595326_1615754_1615880%2C00.html |archivedate=August 24, 2013 |df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/2007/article/0,28804,1733748_1733752_1735741,00.html |work=Time |title=The 2008 Time 100 |date=April 30, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130822203800/http://www.time.com/time/specials/2007/article/0%2C28804%2C1733748_1733752_1735741%2C00.html |archivedate=August 22, 2013 |df=}}</ref> He is sometimes described as one of the most handsome men in the world.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,1559649,00.html |title=George Clooney Named PEOPLE's Sexiest Man Alive |date=November 15, 2006 |work=[[People (magazine)|People]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.femalefirst.co.uk/celebrity/George+Clooney-2021.html |title=George Clooney voted world's most beautiful man |publisher=Femalefirst.co.uk |accessdate=March 4, 2015}}</ref> In 2005, ''[[TV Guide]]'' ranked Clooney No. 1 on its \"50 Sexiest Stars of All Time\" list.<ref>{{cite book |title=TV Guide Book of Lists |url=https://archive.org/details/tvguidebookoflis0000unse |url-access=registration |year=2007 |publisher=Running Press |isbn=978-0-7624-3007-9 |page=[https://archive.org/details/tvguidebookoflis0000unse/page/201 201]}}</ref> The cover story in a February 2008 issue of ''Time'' magazine was headlined with: \"George Clooney: The last movie star\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1715285,00.html |title=George Clooney: The Last Movie Star |last=Stein |first=Joel |date=February 20, 2008 |work=Time|access-date=October 11, 2018 |language=en-US |issn=0040-781X}}</ref>\n\nHe was parodied in the ''South Park'' episode \"[[Smug Alert!]]\", which criticizes his acceptance speech at the [[78th Academy Awards]].{{citation needed|date=June 2019}} Clooney has also lent his voice to ''South Park'' as Sparky the Dog in \"[[Big Gay Al's Big Gay Boat Ride]]\" and as the emergency room doctor in ''[[South Park: Bigger, Longer & Uncut]]''. Clooney was caricatured in the ''[[American Dad!]]'' episode \"[[Tears of a Clooney]]\", in which [[Francine Smith]] plans to destroy him.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tears of a Clooney |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b007946d |accessdate=May 15, 2013 |publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\nDirector [[Alec Cartio|Alexander Cartio]] made his debut feature film, ''[[Convincing Clooney]]'', about a Los Angeles artist who, faced with rejection as an [[actor]] and [[screenwriter]], concocts a master plan to get Clooney to star in his first-ever low-budget short film. The movie was released on DVD in November 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iZBk92SG-9Y |title=''Convincing Clooney by Alexander Cartio \u2013 Official movie trailer |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=June 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n'''Articles'''\n* [https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/central-african-republic/2018-03-14/key-making-peace-africa \"The Key to Making Peace in Africa\"]. Co-authored with [[John Prendergast (activist)|John Prendergast]]. ''[[Foreign Affairs]]'', Vol. 97, No. 2, March 14, 2018.\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by George Clooney}}\nThroughout his career, Clooney has won two [[Academy Awards]], one for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for his role in ''[[Syriana]]''<ref>{{cite web |title=George Clooney Wins Supporting Actor: 2006 Oscars |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NqDbG9h-f7c |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=August 30, 2014}}</ref> and one for [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] as one of the producers for ''[[Argo (2012 film)|Argo]]'', as well as a [[BAFTA Award for Best Film|BAFTA]] and a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Drama|Golden Globe]]. For his role in ''[[The Descendants]]'', he won a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Drama|Golden Globe Award]]<ref>{{cite web |title=2012 Golden Globes: 'Descendants,' Clooney win |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/movies/movieawards/goldenglobes/story/2012-01-13/Golden-Globes-news/52536558/1 |work=USA Today |accessdate=August 30, 2014}}</ref> and was nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Academy Award]], [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|BAFTA Award]], [[Satellite Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture|Satellite Award]], and two [[Screen Actors Guild Awards]]: [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Leading Role|Best Lead Actor]] and [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture|Best Cast]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The Descendants (2011) Awards |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1033575/awards |publisher=Internet Movie Database |accessdate=August 30, 2014}}</ref> On January 11, 2015, Clooney was awarded the Golden Globe [[Golden Globe Cecil B. DeMille Award|Cecil B. DeMille Lifetime Achievement Award]].\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Main|George Clooney filmography}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links|wikt=no |commons=George Clooney |b=no |n=no |q=George Clooney |s=no |v=no |species=no }}\n* {{IMDb name}}\n* {{AllMovie person}}\n* {{TCMDb name}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes person|george_clooney}}\n* {{Metacritic person}}\n\n{{George Clooney}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of awards and nominations received by George Clooney|Awards for George Clooney]]\n|list =\n{{